The fruit of 
 M. balsamina contains the red, soft flesh that surround the edible seed (
 Tan C. et al., 2015; 
 Birla, 2016; 
 Devyani et al., 2016; 
 Souda et al., 2018). The tender fruits and shoots of 
 M. balsamina are usually boiled with meat and both can be decided to be added to the soup. Young fruits of 
 M. balsamina are cooked and eaten, after peeling it is advisable to put on the salt water to minimize the bitterness before cooking, additionally the South Africans and Nigerians appreciate the fruit for its better taste (
 Acquaviva et al., 2013; 
 Ghosh, 2014; 
 Souda et al., 2018). The fruits of 
 M. balsamina are frequent ingredients used in Indo Pakistan pickles and they are often used in curries and meat dishes.
